sec.p:
Among the possible reduction products of CO2RR on the cathode, formic acid (HCOOH) is of great significance as it can serve as vital chemical intermediate in many industrial processes, a potential liquid compound for hydrogen storage, and even a fuel to be directly used in formic acid fuel cells11–13. For the anodic reaction, a promising candidate is the oxidation of 5-hydroxymethylfurfural (HMF), a lignocellulosic biomass-derived small molecule14. Owning to the presence of active hydroxyl and aldehyde groups, HMF can be transformed into various high-value chemical precursors useful for chemical industries14,15. Specifically, 2,5-furandicarboxylic acid (FDCA), resulting from HMF through oxidation of its two oxygen-containing groups into carboxyl, is one of the top 12 sugar-derived platform chemicals claimed by the U.S. Department of Energy16,17. Therefore, the electrochemical coupling of cathodic CO2RR with anodic HMF oxidation reaction (HMFOR) should hold great promise for synchronous production of value-added chemicals (e.g., HCOOH and FDCA) within one electrolysis cell (Fig. 1a). The half-cell and overall reactions involving in Fig. 1a are shown below.1Anodereaction:HMF+6OH−→FDCA+4H2O+6e−\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
